metadata.name: Pseudopodia #28
metadata.description:
Pseudopods are small temporary growths used by micro-organisms for moving about or ingesting food. Here is an artistic depiction of many pseudopods as viewed under the microscope.

Be patient, there are 3 rather slow drawing passes, followed by a final quick pass. The drawing passes give the piece a 3-dimensional aspect.

Press "s" to save image as a .png file.

metadata.name: Faux #154
metadata.description:
This project is borne out of my longstanding fascination with brushwork, and the intricate textures that can be created with a brush, some paint and a canvas. Brush strokes are simulated using many overlapping lines and given texture and depth using a custom shader. Another important aspect of this work, is the composite forms that are created by the brush strokes, which are my attempt to emulate the emphatic energy of many abstract painters that have come before me. Color palettes are named after common paint colors, based on the background color used for the palette.

Those who collect during the first tier of the Dutch Auction can claim a signed print. They will be printed on A3 Hahnemuhle Photo Rag, and shipped to the collector free of charge. More details on how to claim a print and specify the necessary shipping information will be provided via the artists twitter (@landlinesart1).

In live mode, add &size=<YOUR_PIXEL_SIZE> to change the pixel size of the image for export (Right click to save). For example, &size=4000 will set the width of the image to be 4000 pixels.

metadata.name: Dencity #903
metadata.description:
Dencity is a generative art project inspired by aerial views of cities with a high density of buildings. Its perspective effect, its perfectly imprecise lines, its subtle textures and its very advanced level of detail give it the appearance of a hand-drawn work.

Behind the visible art (the image) hides another form of art, an extremely complex algorithm capable of calculating and drawing in 2D each variation of the Dencity project. To draw a variation, the algorithm notably takes around 3,000,000 to 20,000,000 random decisions based on the hash of the mint and draws around 800,000 to 4,000,000 lines to create all the strokes and texture effects.

Made with ❤️, code and p5js.

metadata.name: Tree and Cloud #54
metadata.description:
Tree and Cloud

This project continues my exploration into the realm of generative impressionistic landscapes. In every edition, you'll encounter a solitary tree, standing tall and proud, alongside a single cloud drifting across the canvas. Yet, despite these constants, the compositions exhibit remarkable diversity in their arrangement.

The clouds, in particular, embrace myriad forms. They may shroud the tree in a gentle mist, delicately frame a set of bare branches, conjure the semblance of a face, or take on the appearance of wisps of smoke emanating from a tree ablaze. At times, they become the trailing exhaust of a rocket, create the foundational contours of a mountain crowned by a lone tree, or mimic a boulder descending from the heavens.

Furthermore, the palette of colors and the patterns of organic brushstrokes that breathe life into each scene are a source of boundless diversity. With each new iteration, an entirely unique landscape comes to life, unveiling a fresh perspective on the mesmerizing interplay of nature's elements.

I hope you enjoy this collection!

--------------------------

This is a 100% code generated project. Outputs are created at a default resolution of 1000 x 1500.

Click on the output and use these keys to change the resolution or save the output:
's' - save at current resolution

'2' - change to 2000 x 3000 resolution
'3' - change to 3000 x 4500 resolution
...
'8' - change to 8000 x 12000 resolution

URL Parameters: You can also set the resolution in the url.
To change the resolution append &res=2 (or 3-8)

Copyright 2023 Jeff Clark
--------------------------

All drawing and geometric code created by Jeff Clark using standard javascript and canvas 2D api. Perlin noise was used with support from perlin.js at https://codepen.io/sixsided/pen/emxxea.js

metadata.name: RGB Elementary Cellular Automaton #164
metadata.description:
Stephen Wolfram's Elementary Cellular Automaton where 3 different rules are drawn in the Red, Green and Blue color components of the image.

Rules are selected randomly among a pre-selection of 53 rules from which nice behaviors emerge.

Tokens can have a cell size in the [1; 20] range.

metadata.name: Love #284
metadata.description:
We all experience love at different scales, ranging from scarcely perceived instances of kindness to unforgettable affections shown to us by family and friends, pets and partners. Each of these moments link us to the same boundless and enveloping interconnectedness that persists across space and time: the infinite source of our deepest aspirations.

Like the feeling of simple bliss, ‘Love’ portrays the visceral radiant light and warmth of our innermost joys. By taking a moment to open ourselves up, these swirling worlds of weightless and seemingly infinite brush strokes invite us to slow down and dwell in prismatic intuitive swells.

In doing so, we may find the immense and omnipresent love that needs only our awareness to be felt.

__________

Press 1-9 to load at different scales (1 = 2,000x2,000 (default), 9 = 10,000x10,000)
When zoomed in, once the output is fully loaded, you can click and drag to move around the canvas
Press 'S' to save the image at the current scale
Press 'B' to toggle the background texture on or off
Press 'A' to toggle the loading animation (recommended for very large scales)

Created with p5.js
For third party license information, please see bundle.js.LICENSE.txt

metadata.name: CENTURY-XXX-METAFRANKE #807
metadata.description:
1 of 5 in CENTURY-XXX, Series 2
Edition of 1000

Tribute to Herbert W. Franke
“In Honor of the Dinosaur of Computer Art” 

Herbert W. Franke, a pioneer of computer art, passed away on July 16, 2022 at the age of 95. CENTURY-XXX-METAFRANKE is an homage to Franke’s MONDRIAN software developed for the Texas Instruments TI 99/4 home computer in 1979, and it’s a fundraiser to digitize his archive:

“Our goal is to raise 20,000 Euro so that ZKM Karlsruhe can digitize Herbert W. Franke’s 1,800 manuscripts and make them publicly available. If we raise more money, it will be donated to the Rütgers Foundation which supports children and young adults in Africa so that they can get access to and work with technology.” 

Each frame, a single “pixel” is added to the CENTURY-XXX-METAFRANKE image. When the software first loads, 100,000 frames are run in the background to start things off. Keep it running for hours or days to see it transform entirely — it’s an “infinite animation.”

metadata.name: Mur #300
metadata.description:
Mur is a series of computational drawings of stacked and falling bricks. The bricks are placed in different configurations of walls, towers, stacks and paths, and are then exposed to gravity. 

The graphics are coded with p5.js and the rigid body simulations with ammo.js. In live mode, press 's' to save a screenshot and 'e' to save a high resolution image. Press 't' to toggle textures. 

Each scene is drawn twice, first brick by brick as they fall or stay in place, then the scene as a whole. Mur is optimized for Chrome, uses WebGL and may not work in all browsers.
